    <h3 class="subsection-title">2) Operational data layer</h3>

    <p>
      Another key finding from discovery was how disjointed data use was across the service. Operational data is spread across systems and teams, requiring it to be copied and reworked. This introduces errors, duplication, and reliance on manual extracts.
    </p>

    <p>
      The operational data layer addresses this by creating a single, trusted source of funding data. Changes are made once, with clear audit trails, and flow across the service.
    </p>

    <div class="image-placeholder">[Image: Linear data flow]</div>
    <div class="image-placeholder">[Image: Hub and spoke data model]</div>

    <p>
      This reduces reliance on individual knowledge, improves auditability, and makes the service easier to scale and adapt.
    </p>

    <p>
      Running a complex live service makes prioritisation difficult. Urgent issues are constant, but quick fixes often lead to workarounds that add complexity and variation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thinking about communications and data as service wide problems was made possible by introducing outcome focused teams that could work across system boundaries. This moved us away from reactive fixes and towards end to end solutions.
    </p>

